{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0ccda33d-32a9-4741-9f28-a3fefa3e8328","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace with this configuration:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for C# MCP servers using `ModelContextProtocol` SDK).\n- **`command`/`args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- After saving, open the **MCP panel** in VS Code (or reload) and start the server. Copilot Chat in agent mode (`@workspace`) will then discover your server's tools automatically.\n\nIf your server listens on HTTP/SSE instead of stdio, use `\"type\": \"sse\"` with a `\"url\"` field instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0be7974c-badd-4578-a0c2-75d2a8365ae1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet, but the user said they built it. They're just asking how to configure mcp.json. I can give them the configuration directly.","outputTokens":304},"id":"1504481e-1f60-44ff-b064-42f8539e6768","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:47:30.091Z","parentId":"f31c59a7-511c-4f14-9e83-1f3949f3fa04"}
